[1] Philippines (Ecija)
Date: Wed, 21 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ABS - CBN 21 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/NewsStory.aspx?section=PROVINCIAL&oid=55671>

Dengue infects 64 Ecija children (no deaths)
--------------------------------------------
The dengue fever-carrying mosquito has attacked 6 villages in this town,
sickening 64 children and prompting local health authorities to sound a
distress call.
Town health officer Dahlia Prado said the victims' ages ranged from 4
months to 9 years. There was no reported fatality. She asked the help of
the Department of Health regional office in Cabanatuan City, which, in
turn, sent workers to fog the area to drive the killer mosquitoes away.
The outbreak was reported last week with an initial 49 cases, but on Monday
15 cases more were reported in the predominantly farming barangays
[sectors] of Cablangan, Magsaysay, Osmena, Quezon, Quirino and Roxas in
this town.
Prado suspected that the main cause of the outbreak is the lack of proper
household water supply source, besides the usual lack of basic hygiene and
sanitation facilities in rural areas like Talugtog. Talugtog, some 56 km
northwest of Cabanatuan City, is a 5th-class town. It is one of the 19
Nueva Ecija towns that have no access to potable water supply as reported
recently by the provincial planning and development office.
The deprivation of water source of many Talugtog folk prompted them to
fetch their water from the pumps owned by a few better-off neighbors, if
not directly from rivers and creeks. They would then store their water in
drums and other containers, where the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes could have
bred.
[Byline: Carlos D. Marquez Jr.]
